<title> Researchers have employed a variety of methods to study web search, including analyzing search engine and web browser logs (e.g., [32, 53, 54]), gathering self-report data from surveys, interviews, or diary studies of end-users (e.g., [42, 43]), and recruiting participants to perform controlled search tasks (e.g., [3, 25, 44]). As with any methodology, there are trade-offs: logs can provide in-situ data for a large set of users, but lack qualitative depth; self-report data may have gaps or inconsistencies with actual observed behavior; controlled, in-lab task performance may differ from natural search behavior in unanticipated ways, etc.

